Imagine you have a physical filing cabinet in your room. You turn to your assistant (the computer) and give a very clear instruction:

"Go open the 5th drawer of that cabinet and see what's inside."

Your assistant walks over to the cabinet, looks at it, and immediately realizes there is a major problem: The cabinet only has 3 drawers. 
The 5th drawer does not exist. Your assistant cannot complete the task, panics, and reports back an error. In the programming world, asking 
the computer to look inside a "drawer" that physically isn't there is exactly what triggers an IndexOutOfRangeException.

## The Technical Reality

In programming, when you create an Array, you are allocating a fixed, specific number of "slots" (drawers) in memory to hold data.
Because almost all modern programming languages use zero-based indexing, the counting is always shifted by one. If you have an 
array of 3 items, the available indexes are 0, 1, and 2. If you try to access index [3], the computer looks at the memory block, 
realizes the array stops at [2], and immediately throws an IndexOutOfRangeException to stop you from reading memory that doesn't belong to that array. 

## Let's Look at the Code

// We create an array (a cabinet) with exactly 3 items (drawers).
string[] teams = { "Bucks", "Warriors", "Lakers" };

// How the computer sees the indexes:
// Index 0: "Bucks"
// Index 1: "Warriors"
// Index 2: "Lakers"

// BOOM! The application crashes here.
// We are asking the computer to open drawer number 3, which points to thin air!
Console.WriteLine(teams[3]);
